  "sections": [
    {
      "id": "vowels",
      "number": 1,
      "title": "Vowels",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "headers": [
            "Sound",
            "Example",
            "Notes"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "/a/",
              "<em>chat</em> (cat)",
              "Like English \"ah\""
            ],
            [
              "/e/",
              "<em>été</em> (summer)",
              "Like English \"ay\" but pure, no glide"
            ],
            [
              "/ɛ/",
              "<em>fête</em>, <em>lait</em>",
              "Like English \"eh\""
            ],
            [
              "/i/",
              "<em>vie</em> (life)",
              "Like English \"ee\""
            ],
            [
              "/o/",
              "<em>eau</em>, <em>beau</em>",
              "Like English \"oh\" but pure"
            ],
            [
              "/ɔ/",
              "<em>or</em> (gold)",
              "Like English \"aw\""
            ],
            [
              "/u/",
              "<em>vous</em> (you)",
              "Like English \"oo\" — lips very rounded"
            ],
            [
              "/y/",
              "<em>tu</em> (you informal)",
              "<strong>No English equivalent.</strong> Shape lips for \"oo\", say \"ee\". 🇷🇺 Like the Russian «ю» minus the initial glide"
            ],
            [
              "/ø/",
              "<em>feu</em> (fire)",
              "Shape lips for \"o\", say \"e\""
            ],
            [
              "/œ/",
              "<em>peur</em> (fear)",
              "Like /ø/ but more open"
            ]
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "nasal-vowels-unique-to-french",
      "number": 2,
      "title": "Nasal Vowels — Unique to French",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "These are vowels where air passes through the nose. No consonant \"n\" or \"m\" is pronounced."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "headers": [
            "Spelling",
            "Sound",
            "Example"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "-an, -en, -am, -em",
              "/ɑ̃/",
              "<em>dans, enfant, temps</em>"
            ],
            [
              "-in, -ain, -im",
              "/ɛ̃/",
              "<em>vin, main, simple</em>"
            ],
            [
              "-on, -om",
              "/ɔ̃/",
              "<em>bon, nom</em>"
            ],
            [
              "-un, -um",
              "/œ̃/",
              "<em>un, parfum</em> (merging with /ɛ̃/ in modern speech)"
            ]
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "variant": "compare-ru",
          "text": "🇷🇺 Russian has no nasal vowels — this requires conscious practice. The nasal quality comes from lowering the velum, not from pronouncing an \"n\"."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "the-french-r",
      "number": 3,
      "title": "The French R",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The French /R/ is a uvular fricative — made at the back of the throat, not with the tongue tip."
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "variant": "compare-ru",
          "text": "🇷🇺 It is <strong>not</strong> the Russian \"р\". Think of it as gargling gently. The closest approximation for a Russian speaker is the sound in clearing your throat softly."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "silent-letters-final-consonants",
      "number": 4,
      "title": "Silent Letters & Final Consonants",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "This is crucial. French has massive spelling-pronunciation divergence because of historical silent letters."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "<strong>Rule: Most final consonants are silent.</strong> Exceptions: C, R, F, L (remember: <strong>CaReFuL</strong>)."
        },
        {
          "type": "table",
          "headers": [
            "Written",
            "Pronounced",
            "Not pronounced"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "<em>vous parlez</em>",
              "/vu paʁle/",
              "final -z, -s silent"
            ],
            [
              "<em>grand</em>",
              "/gʁɑ̃/",
              "final -d silent"
            ],
            [
              "<em>chaud</em>",
              "/ʃo/",
              "final -d silent"
            ],
            [
              "<em>chef</em>",
              "/ʃɛf/",
              "-f pronounced (CaReFuL)"
            ],
            [
              "<em>mer</em>",
              "/mɛʁ/",
              "-r pronounced (CaReFuL)"
            ]
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "liaison",
      "number": 5,
      "title": "Liaison",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "When a word ending in a normally-silent consonant is followed by a word beginning with a vowel, the consonant is <strong>pronounced</strong> and links to the next word:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "<em>les enfants</em> → /le‿zɑ̃fɑ̃/ (the z links)",
            "<em>nous avons</em> → /nu‿zavɔ̃/",
            "<em>vous êtes</em> → /vu‿zɛt/"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Liaison is <strong>obligatory</strong> after determiners, pronouns, and auxiliaries; <strong>optional</strong> in careful speech elsewhere; and <strong>forbidden</strong> before aspirated h."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "elision",
      "number": 6,
      "title": "Elision",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The final vowel of short words (le, la, je, me, te, se, de, ne, que) drops before a vowel or mute h:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "items": [
            "<em>le + ami</em> → <em>l'ami</em>",
            "<em>je + ai</em> → <em>j'ai</em>",
            "<em>ne + est</em> → <em>n'est</em>"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "accent-marks",
      "number": 7,
      "title": "Accent Marks",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "table",
          "headers": [
            "Mark",
            "Name",
            "Effect"
          ],
          "rows": [
            [
              "é",
              "accent aigu",
              "/e/ — closed e"
            ],
            [
              "è, ê",
              "accent grave/circonflexe",
              "/ɛ/ — open e"
            ],
            [
              "â, ô",
              "circumflex",
              "historically long vowel; now mostly signals open quality"
            ],
            [
              "ç",
              "cédille",
              "s sound before a, o, u (<em>garçon</em>)"
            ],
            [
              "ë, ï",
              "tréma",
              "vowel is pronounced separately (<em>Noël</em>, <em>naïf</em>)"
            ]
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}